Name: ampere
BaseUnit/Description: The ampere is that constant current which, if maintained in two straight parallel conductors of infinite length, of negligible circular cross section, and placed 1 metre apart in vacuum,would produce between these conductors a force equal to 2 x 10**-7 newton per metre of length.

Name: bel
BaseUnit/Description: A unit of intensity. A bel is the base 10 logarithm of a power or amplitude ratio. Some systems define a specific base value.

Name: bels/octave
BaseUnit/Description: The power or amplitude variation that occurs over a doubling of the domain variable.

Name: baud
BaseUnit/Description: A unit of transmission speed, equal to one bit per second. This unit is being deprecated in favor of bits per second (bps).

Name: bits per second
BaseUnit/Description: A unit of transmission speed, equal to one bit per second.

Name: becquerel
BaseUnit/Description: The activity of a radionuclide decaying at the rate of one spontaneous nuclear transition per second

Name: byte
BaseUnit/Description: The capacity, in bytes, of a storage device or an information system,is one eighth of the base two logarithm of the number of possible states of the device or system.

Name: coulomb
BaseUnit/Description: The time integral of electric current,equal to 1 A.s

Name: candela
BaseUnit/Description: The candela is the luminous intensity, in a given direction,of a source that emits monochromatic radiation of frequency 540 X 10**12 hertz and that has a radian intensity in that direction of 1/683 watt per steradian.

Name: equivalent
BaseUnit/Description: The charge contained in one mole of electrons. The amount is equal to 96487 coulombs.

Name: euclid
BaseUnit/Description: A base unit to describe all dimensionless values,such as ratios and factors.

Name: farad
BaseUnit/Description: The capacitance of a capacitor between the plates of which there appears a difference of potential of 1 V when it is charged by a quantity of electricity equal to 1 C.

Name: gas unit
BaseUnit/Description: Can mean 1/50th per cent or 1/100th percent,depending on country.

Name: API gamma ray units
BaseUnit/Description: A unit defined by the American Petroleum Institute for gamma ray log measurements.

Name: gray
BaseUnit/Description: The absorbed dose when the energy per unit mass imparted to matter by ionizing radiation is 1 J/kg

Name: henry
BaseUnit/Description: The inductance of a closed circuit in which an electromotive force of 1 V is produced when the electric current in the circuit varies uniformly at a rate of 1 A/s.

Name: hertz
BaseUnit/Description: The frequency of a periodic phenomenon of which the period is 1 second.

Name: joule
BaseUnit/Description: The work done when the point of application of a force of 1 N is displaced a distance of 1 m in the direction of the force.

Name: kelvin
BaseUnit/Description: The kelvin, unit of thermodynamic temperature,is the fraction 1/273.16 of the thermodynamic temperature of the triple point of water.

Name: kilogram
BaseUnit/Description: The kilogram is the unit of mass (not force); it is equal to the mass of the international prototype of the kilogram.

Name: lumen
BaseUnit/Description: The luminous flux emitted in a solid angle of 1 sr by a point source having a uniform intensity of 1 cd.

Name: lux
BaseUnit/Description: The illuminance produced by a luminous flux of 1 lm uniformly distributed over a surface of 1 m2.

Name: metre
BaseUnit/Description: The metre is the length equal to 1 650 763.73 wavelengths in vacuum of the radiation corresponding to the transition between the levels 2p10 and 5d5 of the krypton-86 atom.

Name: cubic metres/std cubic metres, 0 deg C
cubic metres/std cubic metres, 15 deg C
mole
BaseUnit/Description: The mole is the amount of substance of a system that contains as many elementary entities as there are atoms in 0.012 kilogram of carbon-12. When the mole is used, the elementary entities must be specified and may be atoms, molecules, ions, electrons, other particles,or specified groups of such particles.

Name: newton
BaseUnit/Description: That force which, when ap0plied to a body having a mass of 1 kg,gives it an acceleration of 1 m/s2.

Name: API neutron units
BaseUnit/Description: A unit defined by the American Petroleum Institute for neutron log measurements.

Name: octave
BaseUnit/Description: The number of octaves between two positive values is the base two logarithm of their ratio.

Name: ohm
BaseUnit/Description: The electric resistance between two points of a conductor when a constant difference of potential of 1 V, applied between these two points, produces in this conductor a current of 1 A,this conductor not being the source of any electromotive force.

Name: pascal
BaseUnit/Description: The pressure or stress of 1 N/m2.

Name: pH
BaseUnit/Description: The negative,base 10 logarithm of the concentration of hydrogen ions in a solution.

Name: radian
BaseUnit/Description: The radian is the plane angle between two radii of a circle that cut of, on the circumference,an arc equal in length to the radius.

Name: siemens
BaseUnit/Description: The electric conductance of a conductor in which a current of 1 A is produced by an electric potential difference of 1 V.

Name: second
BaseUnit/Description: The second is the duration of 9 192 631 770 periods of the radiation corresponding to the transition between the two hyperfine levels of the ground state of the cesium-133 atom.

Name: standard cubic metres at 0 deg Celsius
BaseUnit/Description: A unit of standard volume. The number of scm(0C) of a fluid is the volume the fluid will occupy (in cubic metres) when the fluid is reduced to standard conditions of 1 atm.,0 degrees Celsius.

Name: std cubic metres, 0 deg C/square metre
std cubic metres, 0 deg C/cubic metre
standard cubic metres at 15 deg Celsius
BaseUnit/Description: A unit of standard volume. The number of scm(15C) of a fluid is the volume the fluid will occupy (in cubic metres) when the fluid is reduced to standard conditions of 1 atm.,15 degrees Celsius.

Name: std cubic metres, 15 deg C/square metre
std cubic metres, 15 deg C/cubic metre
steradian
BaseUnit/Description: The steradian is the solid angle that, having its vertex in the center of a circle,cuts of an area of the surface of the sphere equal to that of a square with sides of length equal to the radius of the sphere.

Name: sievert
BaseUnit/Description: The dose equivalent when the absorbed dose of ionizing radiation multiplied by the dimensionless factors Q (quality facot) and N (product of any othe multiplying factors) stipulated by the Intl. Commission on Radiological Protection is 1. J/kg.

Name: sievert per second
BaseUnit/Description: The dose equivalent rate when the absorbed dose per second of ionizing radiation multiplied by the appropriate factors is equivalent to 1 Sievert per second.

Name: tesla
BaseUnit/Description: The magnetic flux density of 1 Wb/m2. Alternatively, it is defined as the magnetic flux density that produces on a 1-m length of wire carrying a current of 1A, oriented normal to the flux density, a force of 1 N,magnetic flux density being defined as an axial vector quantity such that the force exerted on an element of current is equal to the vector product of this element and the magnetic flux density.

Name: volt
BaseUnit/Description: The difference of electric potential between two points of a conductor carrying a constant current of 1 A when the power dissipated between these points is equal to 1 W.

Name: volts/Bel
QuantityType/0: potential difference per per power drop

Name: watt
BaseUnit/Description: The power that represents a rate of energy transfer of 1 J/s.

Name: watts/metre kelvin
QuantityType/0: energy length per time area temperature

Name: weber
BaseUnit/Description: The magnetic flux which, linking a circuit of one turn,produces in it an alectromotive orce of 1 V as it is reduced to zero at a uniform rate in 1 s.
